            <ArticleTitle>Replication fork pausing at protein barriers on chromosomes.</ArticleTitle>
            <ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1002/1873-3468.13481</ELocationID>
            <Abstract>
                <AbstractText>When the cell divides prior to completion of DNA replication, serious DNA damage may occur. Thus, in addition to accuracy, processivity of the replication forks is important. DNA synthesis at replication forks should be completed in time, and forks overcome abberant structures on the template DNA, including damaged sites, using trans-lesion synthesis, occasionally introducing mutations. By contrast, the protein barrier built on DNA is known to block the progression of replication forks at specific chromosomal loci. Such protein barriers avert collision of replication and transcription machineries, or control the recombination of the specific loci. The components and mechanisms of action of protein barriers have been revealed mainly using genetic and biochemical techniques. In addition to proteins involved in replication fork pausing, the interaction of the replicative helicase and DNA polymerase was also found to be essential for replication fork pausing. Here, we present an overview of replication fork pausing at protein barriers. This article is protected by copyright. All rights reserved.</AbstractText>
